50|$|American <b>Jews</b> <b>are</b> largely {{supportive}} of gay rights, though a split exists {{within the group}} by observance. Reform, Reconstructionist, and, increasingly, Conservative, <b>Jews</b> <b>are</b> far more supportive on issues like gay marriage than Orthodox <b>Jews</b> <b>are.</b> A 2007 survey of Conservative Jewish leaders and activists showed that an overwhelming majority now supports gay rabbinical ordination and same-sex marriage. Accordingly, 78% percent of Jewish voters rejected Proposition 8, the bill which banned gay marriage in California. No other ethnic or religious group voted as strongly against it.|$|R
